data.content:
Three breaking changes affect your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes `Func<>`, not `Expression<Func<>>`

Your manual expression tree code **won't compile** because the new overload accepts a plain lambda. Replace the entire block:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. — dynamic conditions go directly inside the lambda body.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — now auto-uniquified & nested paths change

Two sub-changes:

- **Same-named properties** across sibling complex types (e.g. `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street`) now get different column names instead of silently sharing one column. If you relied on the shared column, pin them explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

- **Nested complex types** now use the full path. `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was column `BillingAddress_City`, now becomes `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To keep the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

**If you have existing migrations**, either pin column names as above or generate a new migration (`dotnet ef migrations add FixComplexTypeColumns`) — it will produce column renames.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method now requires an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (for redacted SQL logging). Update your signature:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

You'll need to update **all** method signatures on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
